TL;DR - The food here is not worth the high price of admission.

I've been coming every so often to Urban District Market since they first opened. Since the first visit, the food has been below average with above average prices. I initially chalked this up to them being new and still finding their footing. On this most recent visit, it was clear the below average food was a feature and not a bug.

This most recent food stall rotation introduced a teriyaki rice hamburger, a staple of my childhood. I'll let the pictures do the talking. Suffice it to say the difference between the promo picture and the actual dish was staggering. It is supposed to be a hamburger you eat with your hands; I had to use chopsticks instead because the entire burger fell apart at the slightest touch. The rice was undercooked, shredded lettuce instead of leaf lettuce, and way too much rice for a burger bun. The pork was its only redeeming ingredient and the only one of which I finished.

I describe my dismay at this one food item as a symptom of the larger disregard UDM has for its food products. Not all the food here is as bad as I've described, but the best food here is merely decent at best. The owners of UDM have years of experience from Seoul Food so there's no excuse for offering subpar food on the regular. UDM, please do better. I'll come back and try UDM again if you improve.

Cada visita a El Dorado Latin Grill, se transforma en una experiencia sensorial inolvidable. Desde el primer bocado hasta el último suspiro de satisfacción, uno se ve inmerso en una sinfonía de sabores magistralmente armonizados.

La cocina no solo deleita: emociona.

Cada plato parece concebido con una devoción casi artística, donde la calidad de los ingredientes y la maestría de l@s cocineras  se entrelazan con una elegancia insuperable.

La atención al cliente es, sin lugar a dudas, otro de sus grandes tesoros. El personal se conduce con una cortesía genuina, atentos sin ser intrusivos, amables sin caer en lo artificial. La calidez humana que se respira en el ambiente convierte cada comida en un encuentro íntimo, como si el lugar entero existiera para acogerte.

Este restaurante no solo alimenta el cuerpo, sino también el alma. Es ese rincón especial donde el buen gusto, la hospitalidad y la excelencia se encuentran, recordándonos que, en ocasiones, lo extraordinario sí es posible.

We were absolutely thrilled to stumble upon urban central market! For starters, there’s a full blown Japanese market (aka a konbini) that has everything we were missing since our trip to Tokyo! Several different types of onigiri, egg salad sandwiches, katsu curry, Japanese candy, Japanese ice cream, endless sake options, and instant ramen galore plus so much more. We felt like we teleported to Japan! Next up- we tried food from several food stalls (forgive me I don’t remember the names) but we had an udon bowl (delicious), dumplings (perfectly cooked) and chicken katsu curry (the flavor profile was on point!). My husband and I have traveled all over south east Asia and Japan and the food from here is comparable to what we found there. We are VERY picky when it comes to ethnic cuisine but we are genuinely thrilled this is in our neighborhood and we can’t wait to go back! The drinks from the bar were very well done and nothing is over priced. All around it’s a 10/10. Plus it’s great place to meet up with friends especially if they have kids! Definitely give this place a shot!!!

What happened here?! What happened to the vibrant bustling food court that we visited a few months ago?!

My wife and I stopped in just after this promising food market opened a few months ago. What we saw as we sat at the bar then looked promising and we were looking forward to seeing this operation in full swing once all the tenants were in. We enjoyed some original cocktails at the bar and couldn’t believe how packed it was. We tried various fare from several vendors and enjoyed everything. We promised we’d have to return to try the mouth watering steaks that were coming out piping hot from The Rare Butcher. The smells emanating from these restaurants, at that time, were to die for.

Fast forward a few months to March. Lunchtime. The parking lot was empty which isn’t a good sign. Last time, we had to park two blocks away. Upon entering, this time, there was nary a person inside. We immediately noticed garbage and spilled food at various areas, most notably adjacent to uncleaned tables and garbage cans.

The bar was not operational and was unattended, the restaurant we had intended to go to was either not open or had shut down, and we waited patiently at some other restaurant’s counters but there were zero employees present to take our order or to assist us. The lighting appeared to be dimmed at most and there was zero aroma of any kind of food being cooked.

There was a couple with children playing at the indoor picnic tables and one person working quietly on their computer. The rest of the food hall was vacant.

Perhaps they’re not open for lunch at 1:00 p.m. on a Friday? Perhaps we entered during a fire drill? Maybe vendors are only open on certain days? I don’t know.

We enjoyed looking at all the varieties of pre-packaged ramen at the Asian market. We also noticed they served bottles of wine and cans of beer in their coolers. Perhaps they’re promoting a kind of BYOB atmosphere? It’s all a mystery to us.

We left hungry, and thirsty, feeling like we just escaped an episode of The Last of Us, or Omega Man (if you know).

We considered the adjacent Seoul Food Meat Company but it was just as empty and lonely feeling. There seemed to be a ton of construction in the area so, hopefully, the future nearby tenants can give this seemingly good idea a kick start.

Perhaps we’ll try it again in a few months to see if it’s evolved, or still there at all.

Me and my friends came in to dine. I ordered a kids meal chicken tenders and tater tots combo from the ‘Crispy Patty’. As I go up to retrieved my order, my friend approaches because her chicken sandwich contained undercooked chicken. The employee ask her to wait and grabbed a manager. Since I ordered chicken as well, I decided to look at mine to make sure that it is cooked all the way. I cut into a couple pieces and, they are undercooked. I go back and we all discuss with a female manager that the chicken (which is visibly pink) is undercooked. She insist that the chicken is cooked to temperature and that because it’s “chicken thighs” it will look like that. As we continue to explain to her that this chicken is still not cooked all the way, she tells us there’s “nothing she can do”. So we walked away, dissatisfied and with raw chicken…. Later on we approached another man who worked in the building and he listened to our situation and looked at all the chicken (which we had pulled apart). He was able to cancel my order from being processed and refund my friend for her order as well. I would recommended not ordering from this place as they were willingly and adamant about serving their customers with raw/undercooked chicken. I was really excited to visit this restaurant, especially after living in Japan for five years. Walking in and seeing the small Japanese market brought back great memories, and I loved trying some snacks I’ve missed from Japan’s 7-11 stores—those were amazing.

Unfortunately, the excitement ended when it came to the food. Everything was overly greasy, the udon noodles were rubbery, and the dumplings tasted like they came straight from a freezer—definitely not fresh or soft. The final disappointment was the “soft egg,” which was watery and undercooked. I mentioned this to the staff, only to be condescendingly “educated” about Japanese cuisine by someone who clearly hadn’t experienced authentic Japanese food. I fully understand what a soft egg should be, but this one simply wasn’t right.

Overall, the food fell far below expectations, and the experience was incredibly disappointing. I can see why the restaurant is often empty. Hopefully, some improvements can be made to bring the food quality closer to the authenticity it promises.

Urban District Market in Charlotte is a trendy food hall that offers a diverse range of culinary options in a modern, industrial space.

Located in the heart of the city, it features a mix of local vendors serving everything from comfort food to more adventurous international dishes.

The atmosphere is laid-back yet vibrant, perfect for casual dining or grabbing a quick bite with friends. With its ample seating, craft beverages, and variety of food choices, it's an ideal spot for food lovers and those looking to explore different flavors in one place.

Overall, it's a great addition to Charlotte’s growing food scene.

I dont care if you got a cool looking place if i get served a bun thats stuffed with fallout looking stewed meat with a smidge worth of kimchi. You know youre in the wrong place when no one here in a “asian” themed food court is asian. The matcha was more watered down than my dying overwatered elephant ear, and the only cool aspect was the asian themed grocery store, but you cant mess up prepackaged food. Except the only thing that they did make and package was the strawberry sando which tasted like my childhood communion bread. Way to awaken my religious trauma thanks.  My recommendation if you want authentic asian food, and you want to support actual asian communities, and not some douchecanoe white guy in a suit that wrote a fat check to get this cash grab going i recommend super g mart the dumplings in the back are amazing, and the buns are even better, grab a hello kitty microwave on the way out too.

The matcha cofflee was good tho.

Best place to try a bunch of different asian food! It’s almost like an Optimist Hall for asian food except there is a little supermarket here where you can take home foods and the first place I’ve found in Charlotte that has fresh onigiri !! Will definitely be coming back here.

Met a friend and the kids played in the play area for hours while we ate. Got a crispy chicken sandwich and tater tots at crispy patty and it was really good. Highly recommend for parents of young kids looking for an indoor place to meet up with other parents. The changing station/nursing room was like nothing I’ve ever seen before too. It was so nice.
All of the restaurants are amazing! But don't waste your money at the bar. I bought 2 doubles and spent $80 including a $15 tip. $65 for 2 doubles? No thank you. The food is totally worth it though!

This review is for Bop Bop.

Order spicy tofu soup. Took 20 minutes to make it. Ordered it medium and it was like they didn’t put any chili or seasoning in it.

By the time I got the food, my wife was done with her food from the other stall. My food was lukewarm. I suggest you clean your stove burners because getting warm soup after 20 minutes waiting is pathetic. I asked them for Togo container immediately. Tasted the broth and it was mild (not medium like I requested) with no flavor. Got home and put gochujang and chili flakes to make it actually edible.

Don’t order here, order from Kaudon.
Great place for families

The pasta place has been "coming soon" since the Clinton administration. When is
that mf gonna open? Good grief!
This place is great for a variety reasons: clean, friendly, many food options, Asian market, coffee and family-friendly

Great place for all around AWESOME food. Don’t come here just to eat the burgers and chicken nuggets! ( even though they 🔥 ) It’s an Asian inspired food hall so try something adventurous! The market inside is full of fun items you can’t find anywhere else. Kid friendly and adult oriented.
Love the food here everything from burgers to udon to custard buns
Family friendly

I've been here twice for their Saturday brunch buffet and it's great! Lots of options for everyone and they have a great play area for kids inside and out. Definitely recommend this place for families!
Fantastic experience.  Loved it.

Just had a horrible exp. at the SUPER Mkt (stall) located inside the Urban Dist. Market. I started out as a customer and recently inquired about selling their food in my store here in uptown. Because I just opened my store, I was not able to guarantee the required 40 items per order, just yet. The owner and I discussed that we would catch back up in a month or so with other options but agreed that I would continue to buy retail price. I come in today (Thursday/half off day) like I have the past 3 weeks (Tues & Thurs) and was treated and talked to like I had a tail, worse actually! The "manager" (lady w glasses, when I asked - she wouldn't give me her name) questioned me purchasing 5 meals, when I explained to her the owner was aware,  she says "yeah, I know everything", "this food is personal and this is for your business, correct?" - I said yes. They stopped ringing me up and went to verify with the owner and came back talking to me like I was a liar and trying to hustle them. In short - it was an awful experience. I don't know why the owner would allow this, my assumption is ... they weren't interested in my business at all. I don't even have enough time to share how nasty they spoke to me. Based on the fact that they would allow someone to conduct themselves like this - even after it was verified ... I will not be coming back to this place. The sad/ironic thing is ... I've referred them to everyone I talk to! Food is great!! Behavior and communication is ugly.

Firstly, this is one of the few places in Noda that I frequent regularly. The food stalls can be hit or miss, and sadly at times, I will run into low-quality food with a high price tag. It's hard to justify these prices when the food is below par. For example, today I received a Kalbi steak from The Rare Butcher and was very shocked at the size of it. It was a small scoop of corn and small pieces of meat and one was straight up a bone with a little bit of meat on it - all for almost $40**. I want to support local Asian businesses but I feel as though Urban District Market has fallen off. Sadly, Crispy Patty, KaUdon, and the Mini Market are the only spots that are worth their prices. Maybe it's a quality control issue or short staffing but I know for sure this place isn't hitting its full potential like it used to.

**Edit: Double checked the receipt and the actual total was $38.47 including tip. Despite this, over $30 was spent on a subpar meal even if it was in a togo container :’(

Vibes.. Great spot for a date night or you could just go there if you work from home dope place to try something new to eat. If you’re a foodie, I would definitely suggest the chicken nugget meal it is bomb. ‼️‼️‼️
Great, new food hall.  It's well done and a fun place to hang out.  Good selection of food places, too

Cute concept, the food just needed some work mainly because it was missing that kick of flavor that you want, the exception was the mochi coffee place that had great mango tea and donuts! Very kid friendly place though!
Lots of great East Asian food options with a cool vibe

I'm a nanny who frequents Urban District Market every week. This morning myself and another nanny were told we could not bring inside food in by Ish a worker at the super mart that sits in the middle of the building. Which we completely understood most of the time we buy lunch there anyway, we've had numerous occasions when we've had outside food and we've never had an issue. She then proceeds to tell us that we can't feed our 2.5 year old kids their lunch as well. We could visibly see other people feeding their children outside food and nothing was said to them in the same regard. There were no signs visible nor a policy on there website that reflects what we were told. I approached her again to further inquire why we couldn't feed the kids she was condescending, nasty, and rude. We asked her for her managers name and she refused to give it. We then tried to approach the manager to remedy the situation and we were blatantly ignored. We decided to leave and on our way out we approached a group of moms who had outside food as well. They said no one has ever said anything to them. They went up to inquire and she told them it was fine for the kids to eat after telling us numerous times they could not. This situation has left me feeling profiled and disgusted at the ignorance that I was subjected to this morning especially with no management to talk to to remedy the situation. I will no longer support this business and I think future patron should consider spending their money elsewhere.

The food was great and the omnience was better. They had books you can trade in and did I mention the live music?! Ohhhh the Mukbang Ramen from Korea, the hankang Ramen, they had it there. I love it. It my new favorite hot spot. Actually, I go mostly because I don't have to watch my kids run around! Lol. Highly recommend
뉴욕에서 왔는데 여기 너무 좋아요 손녀를 데리고 왔는데 손녀가 하루 종일 놀 수 있어서 너무 편하고 좋았어요 밥도 맛있고 심지어 동물 이벤트도 있어서 참 재밌는 시간을 보내고 갑니다 감사합니다 다음에 꼭 방문하겠습니다

A place thats kid, dog, and drink friendly. Theres something here for anyone - enjoy brunch while the kids play or swing by for special events and holidays. Bring your drinking buddies after work or to hang out on the weekend at the multiple bars and karaoke or just grab a coffee. This place has a vast variety of foods from different cultures and a friendly staff. They try new things and are always improving their menus and attractions.

At first, I was a bit skeptical  but… I love this place!!! let me tell you my daughter will not leave. She climbs the whole place! Its so kid friendly! I highly recommended to anyone that has kids. The food is really good too. I usually go on the weekends for the brunch. And I’m from New York I’m very picky when it comes to food

Went on a Friday night and it was like ChuckECheese. Kids running around EVERYWHERE. Buns were bland, Korean corn dog place was out of corn dogs, no menus to be found, and it was all just as expensive as any good casual spot in charlotte. Will not go again.

Great concept. Cute space. Food fell short on every level from every stall/concept. None of the food was cooked/presented as described. Egg drop sandwich which was advertised as warm was served as chilled egg salad with cold American cheese slices. Most food was very under seasoned and not prepared properly. “Grilled” wedge salad not grilled, crispy rice not served warm and was just cold rice in a ring mold, not seared or crispy at all, chicken skins were soggy and unseasoned. There seemed to be zero culinary knowledge from anyone working there. Brunch buffet was barren and lackluster, not worth the $35 price tag. The very few employees we encountered severely lacked any customer service skills.
Second time here and continues to be a let down. If you have any sort of food allergy- good luck. Very little knowledge or information options. Great idea for the area, but a flop.

It's a cute area with a cute little shop where you can buy asian food products. However, the food within the establishment was below par. Many of the items I did not even halfway finish because they were youre typical standard fried food. I do like that they have areas for children to play. But, to be honest, it felt like a well maintained mall food court with expensive food.

Stick Street was an okay corndog. The top of the corndog was filled with mozzarella cheese, and the corndog was a typical hotdog. Nothing special.

Crispy Patty served a fried hamburger patty. Chicken nuggets were your avergae nuggets. Either item honestly  was not really well flavored.

HC Burger company did have some very yummy bulgolgi. We had the Bulgogi melt, and that was yummy. Very flavorful. Took forever to get our food. However, it was my favorite thing we tried.

And the Labratory was meh. The strawberry mule was full of ice and lacked any type of flavor.

Overall, it is a more expensive way to try fried food. Better, less expensive, restaurants are out there.

I’ve lived in Charlotte for 26 years and this is one of my favorite family friendly spots in the city! Delicious food, two children’s play areas, abundant space and easy parking make for an awesome experience. The food hall includes two nursing mothers rooms and the best changing station area I’ve ever seen. The homemade beef noodles from KaUdon were delicious and the croffle from & Coffee was the perfect unique sweet treat. My family can’t wait to go back! Do not miss this incredible gem!

Must visit! Definitely if you have little kids, so much fun for them. All Asian  food court is spectacular and the shop were u can by beer and wine to enjoy and is
reasonably priced only makes it best place to go.

Severely underrated! Some real gems mixed into the food stalls, highlights are the shaved ice desserts and spicy tofu soup. Great place to bring friend and kids. Two play areas inside and the playground, splash pad, and trail in between soul food and urban district market.
Personally I was a little disappointed by the food. The highlight was the coffee and dessert. It was a great place for the kids to play and parents to grab a drink/coffee.

The food was cold when I received it. The cooks didn’t speak English, so a member of the janitorial staff had to answer questions about the menu options. The atmosphere was nice with a spot for the kiddos to play.
Lovely place. Great selection of establishments, parking is a nightmare however

My gf and I were looking at places to eat for our date night and found UDM. However with so many options I asked a staff member for recommendations. Mr. Lorenzo recommended the egg sandwich and also the katsu sandwich. They are both exceptionally delicious and I honestly wanna go back just for those items alone even with all the other options. I didn't see non alcoholic drink options at first so I went back to Lorenzo and he told me about several options in the dining hall. He was incredibly knowledgeable, polite and kind. He made the UDM experience way more pleasant and I had a great time there with the advice he gave me. I'm definitely bringing friends and family here.

My fiancée and I often frequent UDM, especially during my craving of the lavender gin drink - which is amazing and frothy. But, I was called to write a review at this time because of the workers. I am incredibly happy with the service provided by the workers who clean behind us. They are so prompt, kind, and considerate. I absolutely love our brief interacts, and it makes the experience so comfortable and clean…

So, I was able to obtain the name of the worker - sel-frado was amazing and we were incredibly happy to have met him today!

i heard bad reviews about this place but that didnt stop me for seeing for myself! The la(bar)tory was awesome! very well made drinks. food was GREAT and super cheap! live music, dope market with Japanese snacks & ramen! I cannot wait to come back and have more food to try!

Feels like a more upscale Optimist Hall, tbh. Wish there were more food options, but given the space it’s not unexpected. Being able to get bottles of soju from the mini mart, a cocktail or beer from the bar, and order from any of the restaurants all separate is pretty nice. All of the food I’ve tried so far has been phenomenal. Environment is clean, seating is good. Can’t ask for much else.

Overall, the food was really good.  We tried a couple drinks at Laboratory, Crispy Patty, Stick Street, Udon, and Stuffed.

The Soju drinks were really good!  Highly recommend.

The Spicy Chicken Sandwich was just okay.  It was a little overcooked, and not too flavorful.

Tried a variety of things at Stick Street.  They were mostly good.  I recommend this place.

Udon was really good, highly recommended.

Stuffed was also really good!

There were was highs and lows, the lows caused a one star loss, but overall really good, and will definitely come back!

Went to enjoy the breakfast buffet… $36 for very limited COLD options. An omelet bar with nobody working it, so there goes that option. Shrimp cocktail with shrimp that were not properly cleaned and deveined. Samosas that were filled with absolutely nothing but air. And the $5 Bloody Mary bar? Oh yeah that’s not available anymore. -1/10 experience.

I highly recommend the stone bowl at bop bop! It's a build your own rice bowl. There are a lot of veggie and protein options, but they are not listed on the sign.  When you go up to the register you can select stone bowl and see all of the options. The  beef bulgogi is my personal favorite!
There are also some fun desserts in the freezers located close to bop bop! We also tried a chocolate crunch donut from the coffee shop. It was delicious!

I don't know what UDM is trying to be, but this shouldn't be it. The food options are okay from a selection standpoint, but I have legit concerns about food safety. At one stall, tempura vegetable and seafood selections are sitting under what should be heat lamps, but they are just light bulbs. Those items were almost cool to the touch (including the shrimp and fish), and stale. Not worth the expense at all. Dumplings at another stall were a mixed bag - some were hot, others were room temp at best. At a street food vendor, scallops were served cooked to only about 75% doneness, but were at least kept cold prior to cooking. At the supermarket, various onigiri (including seafood options) are confusingly available from both a cooler and a dry-goods shelf. I guess you decide whether you want food poisoning or not??

The biggest irk of the entire experience though? Unless you want a cocktail, the ONLY drink options in the entire place seem to be a cash-only Pepsi vending machine, or overpriced bottled lemonades from the supermarket. Interesting, considering the entire place is cashless, otherwise.

There are is also a children's play zone inside, which should be nice - but the toys seem like they came from a thrift shop. Luckily, there are hand sanitizer stations nearby! You'll need them.

With Optimist Hall just around the corner, save yourself the heartache and steer clear.
Food was amazing. Try the Niku Udon at Ka Udon!

This was my first time going to the Urban District Market. I like the different food options inside and the relaxed atmosphere that we had our meeting in. I ate at Ka Udon & Stuffed! My favorite was Stuffed and I got I had the steamed shrimp dumplings & the deep fried pork ones. They were so good they didn't make it to the picture lol. The Ka Udon noodles I got was ok, was lacking some flavor in my opinion.
Delicious Udon!  Delicious Onigiri!  I'll be back!

This place has a great vibe and great promise. We ordered food from 3 stalls and dirt was variable - the Korean bowl was spectacular; the Udon noodles were tasty and satisfying, and the dumplings were underwhelming. I really loved the retail area that included Asian condiments from non-grocery store brands at reasonable prices. And clearly it is the place to be if you have a toddler and still want to enjoy a night out; they have a nice and well-subscribed indoor play area. We went during cold weather and are looking forward to going back

My only real complaint is that the food stalls could use better explanation on their displays - of the process of building your bowl, in some cases of pricing, and especially in the case of the tempura sandwich place, of the names of the food items that are pictured!

Most importantly it is no optimist hall.
Starting with the lack of parking this place was a disappointment from start to finish.

It has a nice look to it and the highlights were the laboratory soju bar and the Korean style market. Both were worthwhile

The lowlights were the lackluster food (compared to OH) the outrageous prices (compared to OH) and the nearly 30 minute wait to get food when there were no customers ahead of us. Our group ordered from five different stands at 3 pm on Sunday when no one was ordering food and the times for food were from 12 minutes for sticks to 28 minutes at bop bop.

The thing that absolutely ruined this place for our group was that it is RugRat central here.  Literally we counted over 60 kids.

If you are late 20s with your 3 year old this place is great. But our party was 15 to 42 years old and didn't appreciate the misbehaved children.

My recommendation is go here only on a weekday and go to monarch market or optimist hall for a better experience.
Kaudon: slow service, bad food

We have been hearing about UDM for a few months and finally tried it when our friends were in town from Asheville this weekend. From the moment we walked in, we all were obsessed! The entire place is so clean, kid-friendly and the overall vibe was awesome! We tried several of the food stalls and got drinks which were delicious. The food was absolutely incredible. Ish, the manager was so friendly and accommodating to us after we waited a little while to order drinks because the venue was slammed! This is such a hidden gem and so perfect for Charlotte. We can’t wait to make this a regular outing for food and playtime for our little one.

Parking was impossible at 4:45pm on a Saturday. $55 for 3 burgers with fries (that doesn’t include drinks).  Burger was Meh at best. Kids area was a zoo. Can’t even imagine what this place will be like once the weather gets better. Do yourself a favor and stick to optimist hall if you’re looking for a food hall.
Awful, food is ridiculously overpriced. Charging NY prices but it’s not NY.  Food was salty and bland.

It’s decent at best. The burgers are dry. I tried some food from Stuffed (Asian dumplings) and that was good. &Coffee has good drinks. But nothing is mind blowing. I don’t like the idea that no one is talking to me when I order. It’s just screens. And if you have a question about an item (because some descriptions are left) no one can answer you because they don’t speak English. A smile and a look will not answer my question, beloved. It gives AI generated. Nothing personable about it. Doesn’t seem well thought out. These new food halls are cute but they’re no Optimist Hall.
it was just nasty, no flavor at all

Second time visiting-  first visit ordered a tea with Splenda-  paid for a tea with Splenda- just for them to point at the sweetener  container after and tell me this is the options- should have told me when I ordered that they don’t have Splenda …. Then I moved to another area to get a soda instead  and every  food spot in there that I talked to just told me  “no English” when asking for a soda at a food establishment.  I’m all for hiring people with other primary languages-  but if you’re coming to the register then you need to know at the very  least how to communicate about what the customers want to purchase.

On the second visit I went ahead and brought my own drink- planning to eat lunch-  they made it clear They don’t care to loose business , when asking them to turn tv off in the kid areas. They refused, in the entire building  there is no space  without tvs-  so to ask to turn the tv off  in the space I was in with the kids who do not  get screen-time - and have that refused - even though the one person I was having a playdate with who was with us  was ok with it being turned off ….now instead of  coming here on a weekly basis for lunch with friends group and kids and creating a local spot to bring them-  we will be going  to optimist hall or other venues with kids areas.
Excellent experience, wonderful food we got food from Rare butcher and Boo bop and we love it

We went in the summer when it opened and there weren't many stalls open yet. We got a tonkatsu burger from Crispy Patty and some stuff from Stick Street and thought it was rather pricey for what you get.

We returned recently now that more places opened and were pleased to see more reasonably priced options. A satisfying bowl of jajiang udon at KaUdon was only $9.99.  The fried tempura add ons were not hot, though.

We also tried a hot stone pot from Bop Bop. The menu sign at the stall is misleading. When you order at the kiosk, it becomes clear that $13.99 doesn't include any actual meat. That adds another $1.99-$2.99 depending on what you choose. However, you do get to choose what kind of rice you want (they have purple!) and customize your vegetables. The stone pot really is worth an extra $2 over the regular "rice bowl" to keep everything nice and hot during your meal.

We also checked out the new market. There are a lot of cup ramens for sale, and a hot water dispenser and free toppings "bar" on site.

FYI, there was a sign that the coffee place is currently only open 9 am-4 pm.

And on weekends, there's a brunch buffet for $35.99.

Unfortunately Laboratory was closed when I went but all the food stalls had great options. A bit pricey for standard items like bao buns and beers. Kdogs looked good but I'll have to try them next time.

I finally had the chance to visit Urban District Matket. Great place to visit. Losts of interesting stalls and market. However, I chose to visit Stick Street, and was quite disappointed with the quality of my order. Chicken gizzard, chicken skin, octopus and scallop. The skins were ridiculously small for the order and the skins did not have the fat scraped off of the back of the skin in order to make super crispy, gizzard were horribly undercooked with absolutely no charr,  octopus was soggy and undercooked and lastly scallops were average, nothing to brag about here.

So I tried a variety of things there. Gizzard, spicy boiled eggs, shishito & fried kim roll. Spicy eggs were very bland. No flavor in that sauce whatsoever. The fried kim roll had a funny bitter tastes to it due to the oil. Because the japchae inside has oil, it just made it very oily & it was bland. Gizzard was ok but the sauce had too much sesame oil & it was bland. Shishito peppers were salty. I did not enjoy my food at all. If you're serving simple food as such, flavor needs to be spot on. I was very disappointed.

Interesting place. The whole idea of urban market food court isn't exactly new concept, but this one is somewhat elevated  with Far East twist, which is my current favorite, Korean food is authentic and tasty, Japanese market is fun, and espresso was simply outstanding.
My favorite food hall in Charlotte...the food is yummy the area is so sheek and I appreciate the smaller shops vs a million options that don't meet quality...here it does
Cool places.

My family came here at a late hour and it wasn't packed. We lived out our love for kdramas and anything Asian! Take a walk to the sale section in the back of the market for kimibap and bento boxes, etc. We also made Ramen using the auto hot plate and added all of our favorite ingredients at the 30 second mark. The kimchi was delicious. Everything ordered was prepared from scratch and served hot, yum! Bring some friends and some games to eat and drink well. Next I'll try their brunch.

$2 beers.  What else can I say?

12/26/23 - They raised the beer prices to $5.  Still a great deal.
Loved the food at reasonable price and with kids play area and changing station, wonderful place to take kids!! I will visit regularly from now on!

Very interesting place with elevated food stalls! It is casual but you can get good food. The kebabs were amazing with a lot of different options of meat and veggies. I also tried the ramen stall and it was perfect for a rainy cold day. Everything was good, but the DRINKS were amazing. You can tell they spent time on all of the drinks and the bartenders knew what they were doing!

I was really looking forward to the market but came away so disappointed. I got the Jajang udon and two different types of dumplings. It was just all frozen foods from a package warmed up. Especially at the prices, it’s ridiculous.
Such a cool spot, especially if you love Asian street food. Excited to go for brunch and burgers soon!!
A bit pricey but the variety of Japanese and Korean snacks and food are top tier. I can’t wait to come back and try all the different food stalls here!
Awesome Asian food. Bento boxes and onigiri and udon are great.
Cute, clean, and nice place but that's about all I can say about it.

family friendly
Childrens play area and good fast food

There’s nothing else like this in Charlotte! Perfect for toddlers and kids. Food and drinks are incredible. We’re still confused why it isn’t busier but with two kids under three, we’re probably on different hours than everyone else.

I had the soft shell crab sandwich at Crispy Patty and it was nowhere near great. It was an incredibly small crab on a basic grocery store bun. They give you pickled veggies and teriyaki sauce and it was terrible.

I love this place! Like others have said, it’s very much vibes of foodcourts you’d see in Asia + convenience store where you can load up on instant noodles and snacks to your heart’s content. I’ve tried “Bop” the korean-inspired place and the new udon noodle stall as well, and the price point and value for both are great (sub $15 for loaded bibimbap for example).

It’s still in progress so maybe execution is not perfect on everything but I love what it’s going for and we need more of it in Charlotte!
Stuffed was delicious. Labaratory was fun. We got excellent service everywhere we stopped and the market is so cool!

Decent food served in a space without any character. Prices seem average at best across stalls. Food stalls are all owned by the same group, so no independent chefs or variety in that regard. All orders are placed on kiosks. Almost no interactions with staff. There is essentially zero allergy information or allergy accommodation. This was the most frustrating part because I ended up eating something I shouldn't have. Hope this space stays around for the sake of the overall area, but I would love to see it converted into a true food hall with independent chefs, improved allergy information, and more food accommodations/ ability to request accommodations.
The food was good, kind of pricey. The employees all seemed like they were not too happy to be there, but they still provided good service.

Nicely presented food hall. Card only.  Every vendor station is self service kiosk ordering except for the great Japanese themed convenience store inside which has onigiri and katsu sando and Japanese style prepared sandwiches and bentos along with imported snacks and drinks. I find it easier to park on Brevard and 25th and walk over. It is in a bit of a strange lot geographically so adjacent parking is limited. Indoor decor is nice and new. They have a brunch buffet on weekends and a few other vendors such as Udon still coming soon. Rare butcher stall can order a wood grilled Steak which is cool!

Still in it's early days. But it's a nice food hall. They have an Asian market there. It has some upscale options. There's many outside activities for kids to play and they have a small dog park.. downside is there's no parking. The weekend brunch is something to check out! Will be back
This place gets better every time that I'll come here
I’ve been here 4 times. Every place my girlfriend and I have tried was bland, fast food quality (or worse) and very overpriced. If you’re in the area, Seoul Food is so much better.
Not vegetarian friendly !

Came by for lunch on a whim and am so happy I did. Ate at Stuffed and had fresh, flavorful food. The only downside is that there is barely anyone here. Charlotte people come out and support these new vendors! I had a hard time deciding what to try. Going back in to get dinner for my family and another vendor, and bringing friends back soon!
It's very new place, but needs better restaurant options
Amazing selection of anything you heart could ever desire

Tucked away, new upscale food court. Only about 2/3 of places are open, pricey and slow. Spacious, clean, most operated by the same vendor. Many employees don’t speak English well. Been here twice and needed to order more than one meal to feel full, plus having to buy overpriced drinks at the mini-mart inside. Trying to like this place but it’s not there yet.

This is my second time visiting this food hall and it has been great both times. The first time the were still in the early stages of being open. They had less food options open. I tried a sandwich and two kabobs. This time I tried something from 4 different stands. My favorite out of all of this good food was definitely the Szechuan Shrimp from Stuffed. The flavor on them was amazing! There was nothing I did not like but I was expecting the Stone Bowl to be a soup. None the less all recommended. The prices were pretty reasonable. Everything was under $20 per item. The staff are kind and keep the place clean. We spoke with some of them about recommendations. I hate that I forgot his name but the bartender was kind and made amazing drinks. I definitely believe this place is worth a try. They even have some events or fun activities and a Korean snack area.

We have gone to UDM multiple times recently, and have always found the food to be very delicious. Some of the prices in the shop seem a bit steep, a 12oz Soda can shouldn't cost the same as a 20oz Soda bottle. But otherwise, really nice atmosphere, nice building, and delicious food.
I've been 3 times and everytime I leave disappointed in the food.

Decent spot for quick meals and snacks. Most of the onigiri and convenient foods are very bland. Even at the half off price after 8:30pm, it's not really worth it when the food has zero flavor. Can easily be made at home instead.

I was NOT impressed with the Taco Adventure company. Do not waste your money! The meat was all super bland and reminded me of Sabor. The chicken is grilled chicken strips and not the roasted chicken in the picture. The salsas were watered down and flavorless! The only thing that tasted decent was the tortilla.
Numerous food choices, a small Asian market and a very interesting bar

Cool space and options but took crazy long to get food. We were with a big group and pretty much every shop was slow. That said, all vendors are working hard so not sure what the issue is. Food pretty tasty. Need to come up with better way for people to know what dishes are theirs as everyone hangs around to check all the dishes as they come out.
Sweet place to come for some food and drinks outside. The inside food court has a nice variety but have not tried anything there yet.
We love this Asian-inspired food hall! They are open until late and have a wonderful little supermarket inside.

We went here Monday for lunch, and came back today (Wednesday) to try more! I’m so excited for this place. The food is so good, the prices are great, and the atmosphere is so unique! I think my favorite part is you can build a full meal from a few places, instead of getting your meal from one restaurant.
Definitely coming back for more flavored KitKats from Super, and to try the steak from the Rare Butcher.
Great service and tons of really interesting food options on top of a fun atmosphere right next to the Greenway and Seoul Food in Noda. What more could you ask for?!

Food: Steak served in a very hot skillet tray. Meat continues cooking. The sides - very small - as well served in it. Potato salad got hot and gross. Order came missing extra toppings meat doesn’t rest, burns mouth, etc...

Place: Not all shops are opened yet. Difficult to find menus in some of the food stations - it appears to be all owned by the same operator. Lacks of quaintness of small vendors.
The noodle station - not yet opened - you could see all the prepackaged noodle bowls you could get at the international market for a fraction of the price and add hot water. So it’s hard to tell if the place is authentic or not. Made me wonder if the rest of the food was prepared there or not.

Would give another try for lunch, but would not go there for dinner.

They have a bar.
It’s Dog friendly - outside dog park. Dogs not welcome inside the food court.
It’s Kid friendly - some running and screaming around tables without supervision. And a play area on a corner as well.
Parking on the back behind another restaurant.

We went tonight for the first time and it was terrible.  We first went to stick street. They had shrimp on a skewer. We stood in front of the cash register and the person on duty never acknowledged us, just talking to a coworker so we left. We went to SeoulFood and we tried a beef and chicken bun and wings.  The wings were over cooked and awful (spicy bbq).  The beef was so fatty.  My husband got the street corn which was dry and dipped in Parmesan so heavily you cld not taste anything else. Overall super dirty tables and little parking. We won’t go again.

Has potential but Stuffed is the worst restaurant / “stall” I’ve ever been to. Waited 1 hour for undercooked dumplings.

I’d come back to the market but never eating there again.

Parking was confusing, had to park next door and walk through another restaurant to get there. Some cool food deals, but the flavors and dishes were lacking. The steak was ordered medium rare and served blue-rare, which I still ate, and it was over salted.
All in all, I wouldn’t really recommend this place to anyone.

Much improved! I visited when they first opened and wasn't impressed, but I am very happy to report that the quality has gone up significantly! Bargain prices for draft beer, and really enjoyed the dumplings and the wedge salad. Looking forward to future visits.

The atmosphere is cute at first glance but the food was odd and surprisingly flavorless. We ordered from three different stalls and weren’t impressed with any of the food. The pork steamed buns looked and smelled almost raw. We let management know and they had them remade for us, but, who wants to eat again after biting into raw pork.  Our rice bowl was snagged by another patron before we could get it and the worker almost refused to remake ours….when they did it was mediocre at best.

I love that they attempt to be family friendly but the food definitely needs to work out some kinks. We noticed that the kiosk system at each stall seems like a lame attempt at reducing labor costs since eat stall seemed to have one person working on prep (Thursday night).

We definitely won’t be back anytime soon. It’s missing any local flavor that you get from other food halls in the area.

The food is nasty yall, I came here wanting to give it a try. The chicken tacos were nasty, the dumplings and buns were nasty from stuffed. My husband got the burger from burger company nastyyy! Do not come here to eat. Just come to the Laboratory for the soju.
So so...
Burger company has really good burgers and they service was excellent
my burger was amazing

This might be the first 5 star review I've made for a place that doesn't accept cash.  This is like that other food hall a bit south, but they have $2 draft beers, and nobody is in line for anything.  The food is quick and not bad.  Highly recommend on a weekday.

Great options and serving size at all of their stalls. Their Saturday Brunch Buffet is fresh and delicious. Love the ambiance and that it’s super family/kid friendly. They just opened their market with a TON of options and coffee stall. Highly recommend their coffee!!!
Amazing everything

I’ve really enjoyed this space. In addition to a good variety of stalls, there’s a cool little market with some swag and cafe with a tiny free library. Staff are all very nice. Being on the little sugar creek greenway makes it really accessible. The courtyard between UDM and Seoul is a nice place to work remotely- tonight they were even showing an outdoor movie. ALSO, there are some killer deals after 8:30 on skewers and prepared food. Even though it just opened, I can’t wait to see what this place shapes up to be.
Weak, missed the mark on this one
Really cute setup and nice hangout spot for the whole family. Food isn’t great. Less than subpar.
The food is amazing, a whole bunch of different types of food/dishes you can try, also a little convince section with drinks and snacks and candy, very very amazing experience!

Would go with zero stars. Stuffed dumpling shop served completely raw, not steamed, pork dumplings. This is one of the worst experiences I have ever had at any restaurant in the world.

Do better!!
Doesn't take cash which is pretty weird, i probably won't go back bc the sandwich wasnt very bad

We ordered from stuffed and hc Burger.  They were ok and food halls are always great for a quick bite..but I wouldn't go out of my way for either.  Stuffed has potential but their buns need to be fluffier..they were a bit doughy and the shrimp bun was soggy on the bottom, but the flavor profile was spot on, so hopefully they work out the kinks. Hc Burger was not my thing, I felt lacked flavor and presentation

Such a cute spot with so many options! My friend and I enjoyed the brunch buffet on Saturday morning. So many delicious, fresh options and the staff was very friendly. Must try the steak skewers and sausage Mac and cheese was to die for.
Highly recommend coming here with friends or family. I noticed a cute play area, so this would be great to bring kids as well.

Saw this was open and came for the brunch buffet and was very pleasantly surprised! Normally buffets can be a hit or miss and this was definitely a hit! The mimosa/Bloody Mary bar was very cute and clean. Will definitely be returning and recommend anybody looking for a nice brunch to head this way! All the staff were also extremely nice and welcoming! Also, make sure you check the IG account because that’s is what sold it for us to come over
Couldn’t ask for a better brunch experience!!! Definitely check out insta codes for even BETTER deals!!
The brunch buffet is EVERYTHING. Definitely worth the $$.

I tried the:
Stick street stall: my fellow Asians this is it. Gizzards on the stick, and chicken skins on the sticks were wholesome. I was surprised to see such options in such a whitewashed area.
Bop Bop stall: has both bibimbap, summer version & the stone bowl version, but I think the stonebowl better bc it’s hotter.
The customer services were nice. Parking isn’t bad because we went on a weekday.
We’ll come back and try other stalls soon.

The stall called Taco Adventure is least adventurous taco I have ever eaten. They give you chicken without any seasoning and then also expect you to assemble any of the other ingredients on top for a taco. Their “assortment” of toppings are watery salsa from a ketchup bottle and small raw onions and cilantro. Probably the worst taco I have ever had in my life. Save your money and eat anywhere else. Never again.

Short summary: food was good. Great bicycle parking. Bummer that all of the food kiosks are owned by the same company. Drinks were above average quality.

So we ordered from stuffed, hc burger, and stick street. We had $5 Mimosa bar from labaratory and tried the mango soju.

Ordering from qr code and creating an account to order is mildly annoying. Only one food kiosk required this.

Ambience is open and light with a great amount of color.  They have a kids play area.

All in all I will be back for steak and tacos!
The only good thing I can say about this place is that it's cute inside and the bar they have has good drinks but that's about it the food is not good.

First time here and was very impressed! I tried one of everything and all of it was delicious and fresh. The spiked bubble tea is a must try. I love that the food was made to order. Going back as soon as possible!

Was really excited to hear that a soju distillery had opened in Noda. So imagine my surprise when I see rows of cheap Soju bottles lining the bar that can be purchased at any wine store. I confirmed with the bartender that they haven't started serving their own soju yet. With cocktails priced at almost $20 a drink and it being marketed as a distillery, I found that pretty misleading and unacceptable. The food hall is nice and I have high hopes for it, but LaBARatory may not have been ready to open.
Really cool space and great place for lunch.

Charlotte has come a long way with such a large food hall offering several Asian inspired stalls. I couldn’t help but try almost every single place. Plenty of space to bring family/ friends and for big groups.

What I ate:
Crispy patty: had the shrimp patty with fries. They didn’t skimp on the shrimp and has no fishy aftertastes.

Stick street: fried to order
Sausage and rice cake
Fried shrimp
Kim mari (clear noodles wrapped in nori)
Cinnamon bread with honey

Bop bop: Chipotle style rice bowl but in a sizzling stone pot that makes the rice crispy and hot. Closest to the real thing in Korea!

Stuffed: Bao buns kimchi and pork

I’m full now and need a nap!

Everything we tried here was fabulous! We ate a fried soft shell crab sandwich, a fried chicken sandwich, pork belly on a stick, and a wedge salad. We loved all the options, and the ambiance was perfect. All the stalls weren’t quite open yet, but the items we purchased from the stalls that were open were delicious. In addition, the bar had great local beer selections. It was a fun evening!
UDM is an awesome atmosphere with great food!!!  Highly recommend a visit, folks really know what they're doing there!!!
Always fun and relaxing. Gr8 food

Super cool market / food hall!  Nice indoor space with open seating, a bar area, a grab-and-go grocery (coming soon), restrooms, mother’s rooms / changing tables, as well as water bottle refilling stations & fountains.  Additionally there is a super cool outdoor seating area which connects to the Seoul Food Co. seating area and restaurant.  For bikers, there are plenty of bike racks and even a bike tool station.  Also, for those looking to get drinks outside, there is a outdoor ordering window.  Would recommend to anyone looking for a good food and social spot!

It's brand new with a ton of potential...I'm looking to going back as more options open up. Great location, and everything looks great . The food.... Well... It's not bad, it's just... average. LaBARatory has soju drinks that are not bad, and several local beers, buns from Crispy Patty looked like generic grocery store white bread buns, and the softshell crab was just ok. Stone bowl from Bop Bop wasn't bad, but not as exciting as the presentation. I could get something better from almost any food truck in town. I couldn't justify trying a $30+ steak in this setting from Rare Butcher. It's more of an upscale shopping mall food court than a showcase of local favorites. I really hope that changes.

This place is great, with many of options..for drinks & food. Its a unique opportunity for parents or singles. It can be a date night/day....or pack up the kids and do a family thing. If your in the area...go have some fun, say hello to a new face, and enjoy Charlotte. FYI...grab a steak

Really great atmosphere with food options for everyone. There are still a lot of vendors not open yet so I’ll definitely have to come back when everything is up! I had the Korean rice bowl at BopBop and will definitely be back! Must try the stone bowl! It was a bit pricey (~$18 for the stone bowl with no add ons) but justified for the amount of food you get.

The vibes are pretty bad, and it’s clear immediately on entering that this is a single corporate project rather than actual local tenants. Think like a student union/dining hall and you’ll be close. It’s certainly not optimist hall, but it’s a closer walk from NoDa so maybe some of the additional stalls will help it out.
Really cool space with lots of good food options. Very friendly and inviting space. Have plenty of outlets and seating. No coffee yet but looks like they’re setting it up to open soon.
Food was pretty overpriced for a food hall. The chicken patty we received was also very undercooked.
Rare Butcher was sooo amazing & worth it. Drinks at Labaratory are way over priced. $14 for one shot of malibu is crazy. Also the place has a very awkward vibe.

Had a couple drinks at Labaratory which was fun, but The Rare Butcher was the big hit. Filet mignon from a food stall and it was outstanding. One of the best filets I've had in a while + 2 sides and for way less than you'd pay at a steakhouse.

TL;DR - The food here is not worth the high price of admission.

I've been coming every so often to Urban District Market since they first opened. Since the first visit, the food has been below average with above average prices. I initially chalked this up to them being new and still finding their footing. On this most recent visit, it was clear the below average food was a feature and not a bug.

This most recent food stall rotation introduced a teriyaki rice hamburger, a staple of my childhood. I'll let the pictures do the talking. Suffice it to say the difference between the promo picture and the actual dish was staggering. It is supposed to be a hamburger you eat with your hands; I had to use chopsticks instead because the entire burger fell apart at the slightest touch. The rice was undercooked, shredded lettuce instead of leaf lettuce, and way too much rice for a burger bun. The pork was its only redeeming ingredient and the only one of which I finished.

I describe my dismay at this one food item as a symptom of the larger disregard UDM has for its food products. Not all the food here is as bad as I've described, but the best food here is merely decent at best. The owners of UDM have years of experience from Seoul Food so there's no excuse for offering subpar food on the regular. UDM, please do better. I'll come back and try UDM again if you improve.
Casual, friendly lots of family fun,.and kind of not very busy.

Cada visita a El Dorado Latin Grill, se transforma en una experiencia sensorial inolvidable. Desde el primer bocado hasta el último suspiro de satisfacción, uno se ve inmerso en una sinfonía de sabores magistralmente armonizados.

La cocina no solo deleita: emociona.

Cada plato parece concebido con una devoción casi artística, donde la calidad de los ingredientes y la maestría de l@s cocineras  se entrelazan con una elegancia insuperable.

La atención al cliente es, sin lugar a dudas, otro de sus grandes tesoros. El personal se conduce con una cortesía genuina, atentos sin ser intrusivos, amables sin caer en lo artificial. La calidez humana que se respira en el ambiente convierte cada comida en un encuentro íntimo, como si el lugar entero existiera para acogerte.

Este restaurante no solo alimenta el cuerpo, sino también el alma. Es ese rincón especial donde el buen gusto, la hospitalidad y la excelencia se encuentran, recordándonos que, en ocasiones, lo extraordinario sí es posible.

Love the variety there is something for the whole family. Even if you want to just go for date night with you hubby it will be a fun experience. I did the sneakeasy and it was so fun. I give it a 10/10 highly recommend.

We were absolutely thrilled to stumble upon urban central market! For starters, there’s a full blown Japanese market (aka a konbini) that has everything we were missing since our trip to Tokyo! Several different types of onigiri, egg salad sandwiches, katsu curry, Japanese candy, Japanese ice cream, endless sake options, and instant ramen galore plus so much more. We felt like we teleported to Japan! Next up- we tried food from several food stalls (forgive me I don’t remember the names) but we had an udon bowl (delicious), dumplings (perfectly cooked) and chicken katsu curry (the flavor profile was on point!). My husband and I have traveled all over south east Asia and Japan and the food from here is comparable to what we found there. We are VERY picky when it comes to ethnic cuisine but we are genuinely thrilled this is in our neighborhood and we can’t wait to go back! The drinks from the bar were very well done and nothing is over priced. All around it’s a 10/10. Plus it’s great place to meet up with friends especially if they have kids! Definitely give this place a shot!!!
Play area only for small kids like 2 and under. Burger from HC was all fat only 1/4 edible.
If you have any dietary restrictions avoid this place. No allergy menus are provided had a severe reaction after receiving a dish with dairy after the manager assured us there wasn’t any.
Really good food! My fiance and I tried Stuffed and Crispy Patty and had a pleasant experience at both. Only downside was several of the places were closed. We look forward to trying them next time
Really awesome place to visit. Very eclectic food choices. Super friendly customer service. I highly recommend a visit to the market

The hand chopped burger was my favorite. love the environment and friendly staffs. the food came out very fast and I really enjoy the convenience of  the cashless payment option and they text you when your order is ready.  I will be coming back again soon.
Language barrier was an issue at every station we stopped at.

This place is a 5/5. The food offerings are diverse, and everything we tried was delicious. What really sells it for me is how family-friendly it is—there's a nursing room, multiple play areas, and even a playground. We'll definitely be back often.

Food is good if not slightly over priced for the portions, but it’s understandable considering the location. It’s a great place to bring your kids with other parents. It looks like the place was designed with children in mind and I can appreciate that. Also I only really come for the bingsu which is the bomb.
Raw dumplings

What happened here?! What happened to the vibrant bustling food court that we visited a few months ago?!

My wife and I stopped in just after this promising food market opened a few months ago. What we saw as we sat at the bar then looked promising and we were looking forward to seeing this operation in full swing once all the tenants were in. We enjoyed some original cocktails at the bar and couldn’t believe how packed it was. We tried various fare from several vendors and enjoyed everything. We promised we’d have to return to try the mouth watering steaks that were coming out piping hot from The Rare Butcher. The smells emanating from these restaurants, at that time, were to die for.

Fast forward a few months to March. Lunchtime. The parking lot was empty which isn’t a good sign. Last time, we had to park two blocks away. Upon entering, this time, there was nary a person inside. We immediately noticed garbage and spilled food at various areas, most notably adjacent to uncleaned tables and garbage cans.

The bar was not operational and was unattended, the restaurant we had intended to go to was either not open or had shut down, and we waited patiently at some other restaurant’s counters but there were zero employees present to take our order or to assist us. The lighting appeared to be dimmed at most and there was zero aroma of any kind of food being cooked.

There was a couple with children playing at the indoor picnic tables and one person working quietly on their computer. The rest of the food hall was vacant.

Perhaps they’re not open for lunch at 1:00 p.m. on a Friday? Perhaps we entered during a fire drill? Maybe vendors are only open on certain days? I don’t know.

We enjoyed looking at all the varieties of pre-packaged ramen at the Asian market. We also noticed they served bottles of wine and cans of beer in their coolers. Perhaps they’re promoting a kind of BYOB atmosphere? It’s all a mystery to us.

We left hungry, and thirsty, feeling like we just escaped an episode of The Last of Us, or Omega Man (if you know).

We considered the adjacent Seoul Food Meat Company but it was just as empty and lonely feeling. There seemed to be a ton of construction in the area so, hopefully, the future nearby tenants can give this seemingly good idea a kick start.

Perhaps we’ll try it again in a few months to see if it’s evolved, or still there at all.

Me and my friends came in to dine. I ordered a kids meal chicken tenders and tater tots combo from the ‘Crispy Patty’. As I go up to retrieved my order, my friend approaches because her chicken sandwich contained undercooked chicken. The employee ask her to wait and grabbed a manager. Since I ordered chicken as well, I decided to look at mine to make sure that it is cooked all the way. I cut into a couple pieces and, they are undercooked. I go back and we all discuss with a female manager that the chicken (which is visibly pink) is undercooked. She insist that the chicken is cooked to temperature and that because it’s “chicken thighs” it will look like that. As we continue to explain to her that this chicken is still not cooked all the way, she tells us there’s “nothing she can do”. So we walked away, dissatisfied and with raw chicken…. Later on we approached another man who worked in the building and he listened to our situation and looked at all the chicken (which we had pulled apart). He was able to cancel my order from being processed and refund my friend for her order as well. I would recommended not ordering from this place as they were willingly and adamant about serving their customers with raw/undercooked chicken. However the first manager was not helpful at resolving the situation and again saw with her own eyes the chicken …

SERVICE PEOPLE WORKING IN THE FOOD STALLS ARE ENTITLED AND LOOK LIKE THEY HATE SERVING CUSTOMERS. THEY HAVE ZERO CUSTOMER SERVICE, RUDE, WILL GIVE YOU ANGRY LOOK AND LAST WEEK THAT WE WERE THERE, THIS LADY WORKING IN THE FOOD STALL WHICH SERVES EGG DROP SANDWICHES AND KATSU SANDWICHES , I THINK IT WAS CALLED THE RARE BUTCHER, WAS STARING AT ME ANGRILY WHILE I WAS CHOOSING MY ORDER ON THE COMPUTER. I MEAN WE PAY FOR OUR FOOD AND SERVICES SO WHY DO I HAVE TO ENDURE DISRESPECT?! I WILL NOT BE BACK TO THIS PLACE EVER AGAIN! NEGATIVE STARS FOR SERVICE!
The food was seasoned and prepared perfectly

I was really excited to visit this restaurant, especially after living in Japan for five years. Walking in and seeing the small Japanese market brought back great memories, and I loved trying some snacks I’ve missed from Japan’s 7-11 stores—those were amazing.

Unfortunately, the excitement ended when it came to the food. Everything was overly greasy, the udon noodles were rubbery, and the dumplings tasted like they came straight from a freezer—definitely not fresh or soft. The final disappointment was the “soft egg,” which was watery and undercooked. I mentioned this to the staff, only to be condescendingly “educated” about Japanese cuisine by someone who clearly hadn’t experienced authentic Japanese food. I fully understand what a soft egg should be, but this one simply wasn’t right.

Overall, the food fell far below expectations, and the experience was incredibly disappointing. I can see why the restaurant is often empty. Hopefully, some improvements can be made to bring the food quality closer to the authenticity it promises.
Food is absolutely amazing. I got udon noodles and a Korean corn dog. Atmosphere was nice and calm. I love that there is a store side so you can buy drinks and snacks.

I was so pleasantly surprised to find this international food court in NoDa.  I ordered the spicy miso korean soup from bop bop and loved it, so flavorful.  I enjoyed going through the little market of asian goodies, grabbed a couple of ramen packets and onigiris.

Urban District Market in Charlotte is a trendy food hall that offers a diverse range of culinary options in a modern, industrial space.

Located in the heart of the city, it features a mix of local vendors serving everything from comfort food to more adventurous international dishes.

The atmosphere is laid-back yet vibrant, perfect for casual dining or grabbing a quick bite with friends. With its ample seating, craft beverages, and variety of food choices, it's an ideal spot for food lovers and those looking to explore different flavors in one place.

Overall, it's a great addition to Charlotte’s growing food scene.

This place looks okay when you first walk in, but as you spend more time in here you'll realize everything is cheaply put together. The $20+ soup that I got from the Korean place was so comically bad that I could barely finish it. This spot deserves a 1, because it's hands down one of THE WORST places I've ever eaten at. To add fuel to the fire, it's expensive. They're either straight up paying people for reviews, or they're bringing out people that barely leave the house to know what good Asian food is. Literally, this place is so bad and expensive that I felt compelled to leave this review. I truly hope I save some of y'all the time and money. 🗑️
The food is over priced. Check out Optimist Hall instead.

肉うどんと温玉、舞茸天を注文。出汁が美味しく温玉の選択肢がある時点でだいぶ頑張ってるなという印象だったが、麺のコシがなく茹ですぎというわけでもないのにぶちぶち切れる。口に入れた時のツルッと感は生麺ならではだが、喉越しは何だかねちゃっとしていて微妙。麺というより半生の生地みたいな？舞茸天は先の方はサクサクしていて良かったが硬い根本を切り落としていないので噛みづらかった。

肉と出汁の味付けは良かったのでもう一歩という感じ。
パスタの方も同じキッチンでやってるようなので次回はそちらを試したい

I visited this hidden market for the first time this weekend! 🛒✨ I said hidden because this market doesn’t have as much publicity as other markets. It had a great selection of restaurants, and the Christmas decorations were already up! 🎅 I opted for the Korean place and wasn’t disappointed—the food was delicious! 😋🥢 One small downside was that they served the food in a bowl, not like in the pictures. 🤷🏻‍♀️ #FoodAdventure #HiddenGems #ChristmasVibes
Very unique location with lots of restaurants.   Very kid friendly with an outdoor playground and other kid zones while adults grab an adult beverage, etc.
Great food court area. Added perk if you have kids there’s two play areas inside and small playground outside
By far my favorite place :)
Great food options, friendly staff.
Great spot for hanging out, good food, great drink choices, and awesome play area for kids!

Not as packed and not nearly as overwhelming as the Optimist Hall but Urban District has free parking (not limited to just 90 minutes). Not as many vendors but still a great way to spend an evening.

When we arrived on a late Sunday afternoon, there were a few families with their kids playing in the bouncy area and having a good time.

We did the loop, checking out the food vendors before making choices. A cook-to-order butcher, Mexican, burgers, Asian-fusion pasta, dumplings, ramen and a large Asian packaged food market with coolers of wine, sake, beer and soju plus omakase and sushi. Hard to choose but we did.

With drinks and food ordered, we found a comfortable table. Most of power outlets and there is a free wifi. It's a nice space and I can see it becoming quite busy and fun. We'll return.

A good place to get Korean & Japanese food. Very clean and great service. Will have to go back and try the coffee. Crispy patty is great!

I went to sticky panda and the udon noodle place. Sticky pandas sichuan dumplings were good, the taro bun dessert and pizza empanada were foul.

The udon noodle place (next to sticky panda) i got the pork and udon - it was decent.  A little sweet. It is a simple dish so not much room for error. The noodles were pillowy and soft. I am not sure if it is something I would excitedly get again.

reviews_data.review_text: This is a good food hall. There isn't a great variety, but enough to enjoy it. They used to have great deals in their market on their sushi and bento boxes, which they took away - would frequent more if they brought these back for sure!
This place was awesome - a little gem in CLT!

If you're visiting Charlotte, this is one spot we'd HIGHLY recommend visiting this location. Especially if you're a fan of Japanese and South Korean pop culture.

We got here right when it opened and we got coffee and croffle. A solid breakfast dish that was made very well.

After walking around the place, we found neat gifts and items. We later ordered Udon,  Chicken Katsu, and a few steam buns and dumplings that were actually really well made. Would recommend the restaurants.

Overall, a very cool place to visit with a good selection of food to choose from. Staff was very nice and helpful too!
Stopped by after seeing a TikTok. Enjoyed some udon. Loved it.

Went in for coffee (at & coffee) so I ordered an egg sandwich and cappuccino. The coffee was a bit bitter for my taste but the egg sandwich was delicious. I will come back with friends as this place has a lot to offer .
Great spot and highly recommended. Butcher shop is my go to spot but plenty of other options. Very kid friendly and feel safe when they are playing.

Here is the latest food hall that just recently opened in the NoDa or near the NoDa neighborhood. Very nice, clean and well maintained. It is Asian themed with a lot of the restaurants having Asian food or Asian infused food. They have a Japanese grocery store along with an Anime booth. The food was delicious very filling you need to be really hungry to eat here. The teriyaki burger with rice bun with fries that I got. Was delicious unique. The tempura shrimp and mushroom sticks it got were all good. All the staff was nice and friendly. The play area was also nice. I can bring the girls some day. The outdoor seating area was nice also. Cute place.

Fun food hall with a very culturally diverse set of options! Tons of parking in the back. I’ve been a few times and gotten the bibimbap in the stone bowl - it’s a must try! They also have a small Asian market, boba, noodles, tacos, burgers, fried chicken! Plenty of seating inside too, good vibes

This city needs more classy but affordable eating spots and I’m glad UDM is here to offer that. I loved how the establishment is set up and it’s meant for the professional who has culinary tastes. I enjoy the aesthetics of the entire place including the little dog park and other fun things to do. Not every stall is great but my favorite is the Asian market. It’s a clean set up and reminds me of being in 7-11 in Japan, Hawaii, or Hong Kong.

Very cool place and looking forward to taking friends/family here. If you’re looking for basic American  food please stick to Waffle House or Bojangles but if you’re here wanting to try international food items you’ll be more than pleasantly surprised here.

We enjoyed the Korean stone dish and absolutely loved the bento boxes they offer
Cool place. Great food

I want more people to love this market so it stays around forever. It’s a little hidden so doesn’t get the traffic it deserves, but it should be as busy as Optimist with the selection.
The Japanese market in here called Super is just as good as a 7/11 in Japan, they have onigiri, sushi, bento boxes, ramen, and tons of Japanese snacks, sweets, ice cream, and drinks!
I’ve also tried Crispy Patty and had a great Pork sando, and I just tried Ka Udon and had the best Japanese Beef Curry.
This is a must go, try all the stands, there is something for everyone here.

Charged my card 35$ but was told the it declined so I had to pay 70$ for like 5 snacks that were already wildly overpriced so now have to fight my bank and dispute the charge. This place has untrained staff, useless management and was not only a huge disappointment but a complete waist of a night out. Unless you’re into overpriced plastic trinkets, mediocre food and staff that clearly aren’t trained like they should/management that takes 20 minutes to even show up save yourself and go literally anywhere else!!
Lots of options for food. Also they have a Buffet option, and Togo ready to eat or cook! Must check out! And a cute convenience like area to buy snacks and treats.
Pretty cool food hall.  It’s primarily Korean but has coffee shop, convenience store with Asian food, Japanese noodles, pasta, bar, dumplings. I ate the bop bop place which had very good Korean food
Unique, loved our experience
I really like this place. I wish Greenwood SC would do something like it. & Coffee was great. I had a toasted marshmallow latte.
I can't put my finger on it but it's lacking in many ways.

HORRIBLE!! The food is sub par and not worth the price. Literally took one bite and tossed it. The kids play places are not well kept or clean. It looks like a daycare gone wrong with donated toys. Praying my child doesn’t get sick from touching things. Save your money and time and go elsewhere.
I was unsatisfied I didn't like it or finish the food they must improve in that part the food was all dry
Food selection is limited,  pricy, and not that good. I like the Japanese store there though.
Lots of different options than other halls like this in Charlotte.
Great space! Plenty options to eat and shop. Decent amount of parking, as well.

As far as food courts in Charlotte go, this one is great. It probably has the best variety of unique Asian food of any of the food courts in the city. The prices aren't bad, and the atmosphere is very nice. It also has good play areas for small children which makes it very convenient to visit with the family.
Such a cool place!!

Expectations were high, you could tell they spent a lot of money on creating a nice and cool environment but it fell short on the soul which in the end is the food.

I dont care if you got a cool looking place if i get served a bun thats stuffed with fallout looking stewed meat with a smidge worth of kimchi. You know youre in the wrong place when no one here in a “asian” themed food court is asian. The matcha was more watered down than my dying overwatered elephant ear, and the only cool aspect was the asian themed grocery store, but you cant mess up prepackaged food. Except the only thing that they did make and package was the strawberry sando which tasted like my childhood communion bread. Way to awaken my religious trauma thanks.  My recommendation if you want authentic asian food, and you want to support actual asian communities, and not some douchecanoe white guy in a suit that wrote a fat check to get this cash grab going i recommend super g mart the dumplings in the back are amazing, and the buns are even better, grab a hello kitty microwave on the way out too.

The matcha cofflee was good tho.

Best place to try a bunch of different asian food! It’s almost like an Optimist Hall for asian food except there is a little supermarket here where you can take home foods and the first place I’ve found in Charlotte that has fresh onigiri !! Will definitely be coming back here.

Met a friend and the kids played in the play area for hours while we ate. Got a crispy chicken sandwich and tater tots at crispy patty and it was really good. Highly recommend for parents of young kids looking for an indoor place to meet up with other parents. The changing station/nursing room was like nothing I’ve ever seen before too. It was so nice.
All of the restaurants are amazing! But don't waste your money at the bar. I bought 2 doubles and spent $80 including a $15 tip. $65 for 2 doubles? No thank you. The food is totally worth it though!

This review is for Bop Bop.

Order spicy tofu soup. Took 20 minutes to make it. Ordered it medium and it was like they didn’t put any chili or seasoning in it.

By the time I got the food, my wife was done with her food from the other stall. My food was lukewarm. I suggest you clean your stove burners because getting warm soup after 20 minutes waiting is pathetic. I asked them for Togo container immediately. Tasted the broth and it was mild (not medium like I requested) with no flavor. Got home and put gochujang and chili flakes to make it actually edible.

Don’t order here, order from Kaudon.
